# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: monero-privacy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Individual coin ownership records are stored in a digital ledger or blockchain, which is a computerized database that uses a consensus mechanism to secure transaction records, control the creation of additional coins, and verify the transfer of coin ownership.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The two most common consensus mechanisms are proof of work and proof of stake.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrencies are generally viewed as a distinct asset class in practice.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In 1983, American cryptographer David Chaum conceived of a type of cryptographic electronic money called ecash.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Later, in 1995, he implemented it through Digicash, an early form of cryptographic electronic payments.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Digicash required user software in order to withdraw notes from a bank and designate specific encrypted keys before they could be sent to a recipient.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] This allowed the digital currency to be untraceable by a third party.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In 1996, the National Security Agency published a paper entitled *How to Make a Mint: The Cryptography of Anonymous Electronic Cash*, describing a cryptocurrency system.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The paper was first published in an MIT mailing list (October 1996) and later (April 1997) in *The American Law Review*.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In 1998, Wei Dai described "b-money," an anonymous, distributed electronic cash system.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Shortly thereafter, Nick Szabo described bit gold.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Like bitcoin and other later cryptocurrencies, bit gold was proposed as a digital currency system in which users would generate money by completing proof-of-work functions whose solutions were cryptographically chained and published.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In January 2009, bitcoin was created by pseudonymous developer Satoshi Nakamoto.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] It used SHA-256, a cryptographic hash function, in its proof-of-work scheme.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In April 2011, Namecoin was created as an attempt at forming a decentralized DNS.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In October 2011, Litecoin was released, which used scrypt as its hash function instead of SHA-256.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Peercoin, created in August 2012, used a hybrid of proof-of-work and proof-of-stake.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrency has undergone several periods of growth and retraction, including several bubbles and market crashes, such as in 2011, 2013–2014/15, 2017–2018, and 2021–2023.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In August 2014, the UK announced its Treasury had commissioned a study of cryptocurrencies and what role, if any, they could play in the UK economy.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The study was also to report on whether regulation should be considered.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Its final report was published in 2018, and it issued a consultation on cryptoassets and stablecoins in January 2021.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In June 2021, El Salvador became the first country to accept bitcoin as legal tender, after the Legislative Assembly had voted 62–22 to pass a bill submitted by President Nayib Bukele classifying the cryptocurrency as such.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In August 2021, Cuba followed with Resolution 215 to recognize and regulate cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In September 2021, the government of China, the single largest market for cryptocurrency, declared all cryptocurrency transactions illegal.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] This completed a crackdown on cryptocurrency that had previously banned the operation of intermediaries and miners within China.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In September 2022, the world's second largest cryptocurrency at that time, Ethereum, transitioned its consensus mechanism from proof-of-work (PoW) to proof-of-stake (PoS) in an upgrade process known as "the Merge".
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] According to the Ethereum Founder, the upgrade would cut both Ethereum's energy use and carbon-dioxide emissions by 99.9%.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] On 11 November 2022, FTX Trading Ltd., a cryptocurrency exchange, which also operated a crypto hedge fund, and had been valued at $18 billion, filed for bankruptcy.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] An October 2024 survey from the Pew Research Center found that 63% of adults in the U.S.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] "have little to no confidence that current ways to invest in, trade or use cryptocurrencies are reliable and safe." The survey also reported that 17% of U.S. adults had directly interacted with cryptocurrency, which was statistically unchanged from 2021.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The word "cryptocurrency", in its modern sense, was added to the Oxford English Dictionary in September 2018, with its earliest usage noted as being on Twitter in September 2009; its diminutive, *crypto*, was entered in 2022.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In March 2018 *cryptocurrency* was added to the *Merriam-Webster Dictionary*.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] After the early innovation of bitcoin in 2008 and the early network effect gained by bitcoin, tokens, cryptocurrencies, and other digital assets that were not bitcoin became collectively known during the 2010s as alternative cryptocurrencies, or "**altcoins**".
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Sometimes the term "alt coins" was used, or disparagingly, "**shitcoins**".
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Paul Vigna of *The Wall Street Journal* described altcoins in 2020 as "alternative versions of Bitcoin" given its role as the model protocol for cryptocurrency designers.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] A Polytechnic University of Catalonia thesis in 2021 used a broader description, including not only alternative versions of bitcoin but every cryptocurrency other than bitcoin.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] As of early 2020, there were more than 5,000 cryptocurrencies.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Altcoins often have underlying differences when compared to bitcoin.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] For example, Litecoin aims to process a block every 2.5 minutes, rather than bitcoin's 10 minutes which allows Litecoin to confirm transactions faster than bitcoin.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Another example is Ethereum, which has smart contract functionality that allows decentralized applications to be run on its blockchain.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Ethereum was the most used blockchain in 2020, according to Bloomberg News.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2016, it had the largest "following" of any altcoin, according to the *New York Times*.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Significant market price rallies across multiple altcoin markets are often referred to as an "altseason".
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Stablecoins are cryptocurrencies designed to maintain a stable level of purchasing power.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Notably, these designs are not foolproof, as a number of stablecoins have crashed or lost their peg.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] For example, on 11 May 2022, Terra's stablecoin UST fell from $1 to 26 cents.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The subsequent failure of Terraform Labs resulted in the loss of nearly $40B invested in the Terra and Luna coins.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In September 2022, South Korean prosecutors requested the issuance of an Interpol Red Notice against the company's founder, Do Kwon.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In Hong Kong, the expected regulatory framework for stablecoins in 2023/24 is being shaped and includes a few considerations.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] About 764,000 people who invested after the all time high on 19 January 2025 lost money.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The Melania meme coin experienced extreme volatility in its first days, after which it declined in price.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Memecoins are a category of cryptocurrencies that originated from Internet memes or jokes.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] One example is Dogecoin, a memecoin featuring the Shiba Inu dog from the Doge meme.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Donald Trump and his wife Melania are the subject of their own meme coins, both of which declined in value soon after launch.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Memecoins are known for extreme volatility; for example, the record-high value for a Dogecoin was 73 cents, but that had plunged to 13 cents by mid-2024.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Physical cryptocurrency coins have been made as promotional items and some have become collectibles.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Some of these have a private key embedded in them to access crypto worth a few dollars.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] There have also been attempts to issue bitcoin "bank notes".
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The term "physical bitcoin" is used in the finance industry when investment funds that hold crypto purchased from crypto exchanges put their crypto holdings in a specialised bank called a "custodian".
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] These physical representations of cryptocurrency do not hold any value by themselves; these are only utilized for collectable purposes.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] For example, the first incarnation of the bitcoin Casascius, coins made of silver, brass or aluminum sometimes with gold plating, or Titan Bitcoin, which in silver or gold versions are sought after by numismatists.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The underlying technical system upon which cryptocurrencies are based was created by Satoshi Nakamoto.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Within a proof-of-work system such as bitcoin, the safety, integrity, and balance of ledgers are maintained by a community of mutually distrustful parties referred to as miners.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Miners use their computers to help validate and timestamp transactions, adding them to the ledger in accordance with a particular timestamping scheme.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In a proof-of-stake blockchain, transactions are validated by holders of the associated cryptocurrency, sometimes grouped together in stake pools.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Most cryptocurrencies are designed to gradually decrease the production of that currency, placing a cap on the total amount of that currency that will ever be in circulation.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Compared with ordinary currencies held by financial institutions or kept as cash on hand, cryptocurrencies can be more difficult for seizure by law enforcement.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The validity of each cryptocurrency's coins is provided by a blockchain.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] A blockchain is a continuously growing list of records, called *blocks*, which are linked and secured using cryptography.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Each block typically contains a hash pointer as a link to a previous block, a timestamp, and transaction data.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] By design, blockchains are inherently resistant to modification of the data.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] A blockchain is "an open, distributed ledger that can record transactions between two parties efficiently and in a verifiable and permanent way".
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] For use as a distributed ledger, a blockchain is typically managed by a peer-to-peer network collectively adhering to a protocol for validating new blocks.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be altered retroactively without the alteration of all subsequent blocks, which requires collusion of the network majority.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Blockchains are secure by design and are an example of a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Decentralized consensus has therefore been achieved with a blockchain.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] A "node" is a computer that connects to a cryptocurrency network.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The node supports the cryptocurrency's network through either relaying transactions, validation, or hosting a copy of the blockchain.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In terms of relaying transactions, each network computer (node) has a copy of the blockchain of the cryptocurrency it supports.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] When a transaction is made, the node creating the transaction broadcasts details of the transaction using encryption to other nodes throughout the node network so that the transaction (and every other transaction) is known.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Node owners are either volunteers, those hosted by the organization or body developing the technology, or those incentivised by rewards from the node network.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrencies use various timestamping schemes to "prove" the validity of transactions added to the blockchain ledger without the need for a trusted third party.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The first timestamping scheme invented was the proof-of-work scheme.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The most widely used proof-of-work schemes are based on SHA-256 and scrypt.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Some other hashing algorithms that are used for proof-of-work include CryptoNote, Blake, SHA-3, and X11.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Another method is called the proof-of-stake scheme.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Proof-of-stake is a method of securing a cryptocurrency network and achieving distributed consensus through requesting users to show ownership of a certain amount of currency.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] It is different from proof-of-work systems that run difficult hashing algorithms to validate electronic transactions.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The scheme is largely dependent on the coin, and there is currently no standard form of it.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Some cryptocurrencies use a combined proof-of-work and proof-of-stake scheme.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] On a blockchain, *mining* is the validation of transactions.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] For this effort, successful miners obtain new cryptocurrency as a reward.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The reward decreases transaction fees by creating a complementary incentive to contribute to the processing power of the network.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The rate of generating hashes, which validate any transaction, has been increased by the use of specialized hardware such as FPGAs and ASICs running complex hashing algorithms like SHA-256 and scrypt.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] This arms race for cheaper-yet-efficient machines has existed since bitcoin was introduced in 2009.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Mining is measured by hash rate, typically in TH/s.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] A 2023 IMF working paper found that crypto mining could generate 450 million tons of CO2 emissions by 2027, accounting for 0.7 percent of global emissions, or 1.2 percent of the world total.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] With more people entering the world of virtual currency, generating hashes for validation has become more complex over time, forcing miners to invest increasingly large sums of money to improve computing performance.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Consequently, the reward for finding a hash has diminished and often does not justify the investment in equipment and cooling facilities (to mitigate the heat the equipment produces) and the electricity required to run them.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Popular regions for mining include those with inexpensive electricity, a cold climate, and jurisdictions with clear and conducive regulations.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] By July 2019, bitcoin's electricity consumption was estimated to be approximately 7 gigawatts, around 0.2% of the global total, or equivalent to the energy consumed nationally by Switzerland.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Some miners pool resources, sharing their processing power over a network to split the reward equally, according to the amount of work they contributed to the probability of finding a block.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] A "share" is awarded to members of the mining pool who present a valid partial proof-of-work.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] As of February 2018, the Chinese government has halted trading of virtual currency, banned initial coin offerings, and shut down mining.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Many Chinese miners have since relocated to Canada and Texas.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] One company is operating data centers for mining operations at Canadian oil and gas field sites due to low gas prices.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In June 2018, Hydro Quebec proposed to the provincial government to allocate 500 megawatts of power to crypto companies for mining.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] According to a February 2018 report from *Fortune*, Iceland has become a haven for cryptocurrency miners in part because of its cheap electricity.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In March 2018, the city of Plattsburgh, New York put an 18-month moratorium on all cryptocurrency mining in an effort to preserve natural resources and the "character and direction" of the city.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2021, Kazakhstan became the second-biggest crypto-currency mining country, producing 18.1% of the global exahash rate.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The country built a compound containing 50,000 computers near Ekibastuz.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] An increase in cryptocurrency mining increased the demand for graphics cards (GPU) in 2017.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The computing power of GPUs makes them well-suited to generating hashes.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Popular favorites of cryptocurrency miners, such as Nvidia's GTX 1060 and GTX 1070 graphics cards, as well as AMD's RX 570 and RX 580 GPUs, doubled or tripled in price – or simply went out of stock.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] A GTX 1070 Ti, which was released at a price of $450, sold for as much as $1,100.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Another popular card, the GTX 1060 (6 GB model), released at an MSRP of $250, sold for almost $500.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] RX 570 and RX 580 cards from AMD were out of stock for almost a year.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Miners regularly buy up the entire stock of new GPUs as soon as they are available.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Nvidia has asked retailers to do what they can when it comes to selling GPUs to gamers instead of miners.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Numerous companies developed dedicated crypto-mining accelerator chips, capable of price-performance far higher than that of CPU or GPU mining.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] At one point, Intel marketed its own brand of crypto accelerator chip, named Blockscale.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] A cryptocurrency wallet is a means of storing the public and private "keys" (address) or seed, which can be used to receive or spend the cryptocurrency.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] With the private key, it is possible to write in the public ledger, effectively spending the associated cryptocurrency.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] With the public key, it is possible for others to send currency to the wallet.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] There exist multiple methods of storing keys or seed in a wallet.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Bitcoin is pseudonymous, rather than anonymous; the cryptocurrency in a wallet is not tied to a person but rather to one or more specific keys (or "addresses").
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Thereby, bitcoin owners are not immediately identifiable, but all transactions are publicly available in the blockchain.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Still, cryptocurrency exchanges are often required by law to collect the personal information of their users.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Some cryptocurrencies, such as Monero, Zerocoin, Zerocash, and CryptoNote, implement additional measures to increase privacy, such as by using zero-knowledge proofs.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] A recent 2020 study presented different attacks on privacy in cryptocurrencies.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The attacks demonstrated how the anonymity techniques are not sufficient safeguards.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In order to improve privacy, researchers suggested several different ideas, including new cryptographic schemes and mechanisms for hiding the IP address of the source.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrencies are used primarily outside banking and governmental institutions and are exchanged over the Internet.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Proof-of-work cryptocurrencies, such as bitcoin, offer block rewards incentives for miners.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] There has been an implicit belief that whether miners are paid by block rewards or transaction fees does not affect the security of the blockchain, but a study suggests that this may not be the case under certain circumstances.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The rewards paid to miners increase the supply of the cryptocurrency.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] By making sure that verifying transactions is a costly business, the integrity of the network can be preserved as long as benevolent nodes control a majority of computing power.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The verification algorithm requires a lot of processing power, and thus electricity, in order to make verification costly enough to accurately validate the public blockchain.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Miners have to factor in the costs associated with expensive equipment necessary to stand a chance of solving a hash problem, and consider the significant amount of electrical power in search of the solution.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Generally, the block rewards outweigh electricity and equipment costs, but this may not always be the case.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The current value, not the long-term value, of the cryptocurrency supports the reward scheme to incentivize miners to engage in costly mining activities.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2018, bitcoin's design caused a 1.4% welfare loss compared to an efficient cash system, while a cash system with 2% money growth has a minor 0.003% welfare cost.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The main source for this inefficiency is the large mining cost, which is estimated to be US$360 million per year.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] This translates into users being willing to accept a cash system with an inflation rate of 230% before being better off using bitcoin as a means of payment.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] However, the efficiency of the bitcoin system can be significantly improved by optimizing the rate of coin creation and minimizing transaction fees.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Another potential improvement is to eliminate inefficient mining activities by changing the consensus protocol altogether.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Transaction fees (sometimes also referred to as *miner fees* or *gas fees*) for cryptocurrency depend mainly on the supply of network capacity at the time, versus the demand from the currency holder for a faster transaction.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The ability for the holder to be allowed to set the fee manually often depends on the wallet software used, and central exchanges for cryptocurrency (CEX) usually do not allow the customer to set a custom transaction fee for the transaction.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Their wallet software, such as Coinbase Wallet, however, might support adjusting the fee.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Select cryptocurrency exchanges have offered to let the user choose between different presets of transaction fee values during the currency conversion.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] One of those exchanges, namely **LiteBit**, previously headquartered in the Netherlands, was forced to cease all operations in August 2023, "due to market changes and regulatory pressure".
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The "recommended fee" suggested by the network will often depend on the time of day (due to depending on network load).
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] For Ethereum, transaction fees differ by computational complexity, bandwidth use, and storage needs, while bitcoin transaction fees differ by transaction size and whether the transaction uses SegWit.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In February 2023, the median transaction fee for Ether corresponded to $2.2845, while for bitcoin it corresponded to $0.659.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Some cryptocurrencies have no transaction fees, the most well-known example being Nano (XNO), and instead rely on client-side proof-of-work as the transaction prioritization and anti-spam mechanism.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrency exchanges allow customers to trade cryptocurrencies for other assets, such as conventional fiat money, or to trade between different digital currencies.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Crypto marketplaces do not guarantee that an investor is completing a purchase or trade at the optimal price.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] As a result, as of 2020, it was possible to arbitrage to find the difference in price across several markets.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Atomic swaps are a mechanism where one cryptocurrency can be exchanged directly for another cryptocurrency without the need for a trusted third party, such as an exchange.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Jordan Kelley, founder of Robocoin, launched the first bitcoin ATM in the United States in February 2014.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The kiosk installed in Austin, Texas, is similar to bank ATMs but has scanners to read government-issued identification such as a driver's license, or a passport to confirm users' identities.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] An initial coin offering (ICO) is a controversial means of raising funds for a new cryptocurrency venture.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] An ICO may be used by startups with the intention of avoiding regulation.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In an ICO campaign, a percentage of the cryptocurrency (usually in the form of "tokens") is sold to early backers of the project in exchange for legal tender or other cryptocurrencies, often bitcoin or Ether.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] According to PricewaterhouseCoopers, four of the 10 biggest proposed initial coin offerings have used Switzerland as a base, where they are frequently registered as non-profit foundations.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The market capitalization of a cryptocurrency is calculated by multiplying the price by the number of coins in circulation.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The total cryptocurrency market cap has historically been dominated by bitcoin accounting for at least 50% of the market cap value where altcoins have increased and decreased in market cap value in relation to bitcoin.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Bitcoin's value is largely determined by speculation among other technological limiting factors known as blockchain rewards coded into the architecture technology of bitcoin itself.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The cryptocurrency market cap follows a trend known as the "halving", which is when the block rewards received from bitcoin are halved due to technological mandated limited factors instilled into bitcoin which in turn limits the supply of bitcoin.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] As the date reaches near of a halving (twice thus far historically) the cryptocurrency market cap increases, followed by a downtrend.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] By June 2021, cryptocurrency had begun to be offered by some wealth managers in the US for 401(k)s.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrency prices are much more volatile than established financial assets such as stocks.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] For example, over one week in May 2022, bitcoin lost 20% of its value and Ethereum lost 26%, while Solana and Cardano lost 41% and 35% respectively.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The falls were attributed to warnings about inflation.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] By comparison, in the same week, the Nasdaq tech stock index fell 7.6 per cent and the FTSE 100 was 3.6 per cent down.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In the longer term, of the 10 leading cryptocurrencies identified by the total value of coins in circulation in January 2018, only four (bitcoin, Ethereum, Cardano and Ripple (XRP)) were still in that position in early 2022.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The total value of all cryptocurrencies was $2 trillion at the end of 2021, but had halved nine months later.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The *Wall Street Journal* has commented that the crypto sector has become "intertwined" with the rest of the capital markets and "sensitive to the same forces that drive tech stocks and other risk assets," such as inflation forecasts.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] There are also *centralized* databases, outside of blockchains, that store crypto market data.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Compared to the blockchain, databases perform fast as there is no verification process.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Four of the most popular cryptocurrency market databases are CoinMarketCap, CoinGecko, BraveNewCoin, and Cryptocompare.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] According to Alan Feuer of *The New York Times*, libertarians and anarcho-capitalists were attracted to the philosophical idea behind bitcoin.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Early bitcoin supporter Roger Ver said: "At first, almost everyone who got involved did so for philosophical reasons.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] We saw bitcoin as a great idea, as a way to separate money from the state." Economist Paul Krugman argues that cryptocurrencies like bitcoin are "something of a cult" based in "paranoid fantasies" of government power.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] David Golumbia says that the ideas influencing bitcoin advocates emerge from right-wing extremist movements such as the Liberty Lobby and the John Birch Society and their anti-Central Bank rhetoric, or, more recently, Ron Paul and Tea Party-style libertarianism.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Steve Bannon, who owns a "good stake" in bitcoin, sees cryptocurrency as a form of disruptive populism, taking control back from central authorities.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Bitcoin's founder, Satoshi Nakamoto, supported the idea that cryptocurrencies go well with libertarianism.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] "It's very attractive to the libertarian viewpoint if we can explain it properly," Nakamoto said in 2008.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Monthly cryptocurrency transfers under $10,000 to and from Africa reached $316 million in June 2020, according to Chainalysis data.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Reuters reported that bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies are unregulated in many countries and their legal status is unclear, meaning there is no safety net and little recourse for lost funds.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Some migrants in the United Arab Emirates used cryptocurrencies to send remittances home, claiming lower fees compared with traditional remittance services.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2025, some publicly traded companies announced plans to raise capital to buy and hold bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies as treasury assets.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Reuters reported that the inherent volatility of crypto tokens makes them a poor fit for boards with a low risk appetite, potentially limiting their appeal beyond core industry players.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The rise in the popularity of cryptocurrencies and their adoption by financial institutions has led some governments to assess whether regulation is needed to protect users.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) has defined cryptocurrency-related services as "virtual asset service providers" (VASPs) and recommended that they be regulated with the same money laundering (AML) and know your customer (KYC) requirements as financial institutions.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In May 2020, the Joint Working Group on interVASP Messaging Standards published "IVMS 101", a universal common language for communication of required originator and beneficiary information between VASPs.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The FATF and financial regulators were informed as the data model was developed.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In June 2020, FATF updated its guidance to include the "Travel Rule" for cryptocurrencies, a measure which mandates that VASPs obtain, hold, and exchange information about the originators and beneficiaries of virtual asset transfers.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Subsequent standardized protocol specifications recommended using JSON for relaying data between VASPs and identity services.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] As of December 2020, the IVMS 101 data model has yet to be finalized and ratified by the three global standard setting bodies that created it.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The European Commission published a digital finance strategy in September 2020.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] This included a draft regulation on Markets in Crypto-Assets (MiCA), which aimed to provide a comprehensive regulatory framework for digital assets in the EU.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In June 2021, the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision proposed that banks that held cryptocurrency assets must set aside capital to cover all potential losses.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] For instance, if a bank were to hold bitcoin worth $2 billion, it would be required to set aside enough capital to cover the entire $2 billion.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] This is a more extreme standard than banks are usually held to when it comes to other assets.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] However, this is a proposal and not a regulation.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The IMF has sought seeking a coordinated, consistent and comprehensive approach to supervising cryptocurrencies.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Tobias Adrian, the IMF's financial counsellor and head of its monetary and capital markets department said in a January 2022 interview that "Agreeing global regulations is never quick.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In May 2024, 15 years after the advent of the first blockchain, bitcoin, the US Congress advanced a bill to the full House of Representatives to provide regulatory clarity for digital assets.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In September 2017, China banned ICOs to cause abnormal return from cryptocurrency decreasing during announcement window.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The liquidity changes by banning ICOs in China was temporarily negative while the liquidity effect became positive after news.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] On 18 May 2021, China banned financial institutions and payment companies from being able to provide cryptocurrency transaction related services.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] This led to a sharp fall in the price of the biggest proof of work cryptocurrencies.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] For instance, bitcoin fell 31%, Ethereum fell 44%, Binance Coin fell 32% and Dogecoin fell 30%.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Proof of work mining was the next focus, with regulators in popular mining regions citing the use of electricity generated from highly polluting sources such as coal to create bitcoin and Ethereum.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In September 2021, the Chinese government declared all cryptocurrency transactions of any kind illegal, completing its crackdown on cryptocurrency.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The proposed legislation was criticised by Cook Islands Crown Law's deputy solicitor general David Greig, who described it as "flawed" and said that some provisions were "clearly unconstitutional".
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The Cook Islands Financial Services Development Authority described Drumcliffe's involvement as a conflict of interest.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Similar criticism was echoed by Auckland University of Technology cryptocurrency specialist and senior lecturer Jeff Nijsse and University of Otago political scientist Professor Robert Patman, who described it as government overreach and described it as inconsistent with international law.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Cook Islands Prime Minister Mark Brown defended the legislation as part of the territory's fight against international cybercrime.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] On 9 June 2021, El Salvador announced that it will adopt bitcoin as legal tender, becoming the first country to do so.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] As of 17 January 2025, the European Securities and Markets Authority (ESMA) issued guidance to crypto-asset service providers (CASPs) allowing them to maintain crypto-asset services for non-compliant ARTs and EMTs until the end of March 2025.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The rest of MiCA came into force as of 30 December 2024, covering crypto-assets other than ART and EMT and CASPs.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] MiCA excludes crypto-assets if they qualify as financial instruments according to ESMA guidelines published on 17 December 2024 as well as crypto-assets that are unique and not fungible with other crypto-assets.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] At present, India neither prohibits nor allows investment in the cryptocurrency market.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2020, the Supreme Court of India had lifted the ban on cryptocurrency, which was imposed by the Reserve Bank of India.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Since then, an investment in cryptocurrency is considered legitimate, though there is still ambiguity about the issues regarding the extent and payment of tax on the income accrued thereupon and also its regulatory regime.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] But it is being contemplated that the Indian Parliament will soon pass a specific law to either ban or regulate the cryptocurrency market in India.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] He mooted regulating the cryptocurrency market rather than completely banning it.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] He favoured following IMF and FATF guidelines in this regard.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] South Africa, which has seen a large number of scams related to cryptocurrency, is said to be putting a regulatory timeline in place that will produce a regulatory framework.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The largest scam occurred in April 2021, where the two founders of an African-based cryptocurrency exchange called Africrypt, Raees Cajee and Ameer Cajee, disappeared with $3.8 billion worth of bitcoin.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Additionally, Mirror Trading International disappeared with $170 million worth of cryptocurrency in January 2021.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In March 2021, South Korea implemented new legislation to strengthen their oversight of digital assets.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] This legislation requires all digital asset managers, providers and exchanges to be registered with the Korea Financial Intelligence Unit in order to operate in South Korea.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Registering with this unit requires that all exchanges are certified by the Information Security Management System and that they ensure all customers have real name bank accounts.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] It also requires that the CEO and board members of the exchanges have not been convicted of any crimes and that the exchange holds sufficient levels of deposit insurance to cover losses arising from hacks.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Switzerland was one of the first countries to implement the FATF's Travel Rule.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] FINMA, the Swiss regulator, issued its own guidance to VASPs in 2019.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The guidance followed the FATF's Recommendation 16, with stricter requirements.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] According to FINMA's requirements, VASPs need to verify the identity of the beneficiary of the transfer.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In April 2021, the Central Bank of the Republic of Turkey banned the use of cryptocurrencies and cryptoassets for making purchases on the grounds that the use of cryptocurrencies for such payments poses significant transaction risks.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In the United Kingdom, as of 10 January 2021, all cryptocurrency firms, such as exchanges, advisors and professionals that have either a presence, market product or provide services within the UK market must register with the Financial Conduct Authority.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] On 27 June 2021, the financial watchdog demanded that Binance cease all regulated activities in the UK.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In November 2024, the incoming Labour government confirmed that it will proceed with the regulation of cryptoassets and new UK requirements are expected to come into force in 2026.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2021, 17 US states passed laws and resolutions concerning cryptocurrency regulation.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] This led the Securities and Exchange Commission to start considering what steps to take.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] On 8 July 2021, Senator Elizabeth Warren, part of the Senate Banking Committee, wrote to the chairman of the SEC and demanded answers on cryptocurrency regulation due to the increase in cryptocurrency exchange use and the danger this posed to consumers.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] On 5 August 2021, the chairman, Gary Gensler, responded to Warren's letter and called for legislation focused on "crypto trading, lending and DeFi platforms," because of how vulnerable investors could be when they traded on crypto trading platforms without a broker.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] He also argued that many tokens in the crypto market may be unregistered securities without required disclosures or market oversight.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Additionally, Gensler did not hold back in his criticism of stablecoins.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] These tokens, which are pegged to the value of fiat currencies, may allow individuals to bypass important public policy goals related to traditional banking and financial systems, such as anti-money laundering, tax compliance, and sanctions.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] On 19 October 2021, the first bitcoin-linked exchange-traded fund (ETF) from ProShares started trading on the NYSE under the ticker "BITO." ProShares CEO Michael L.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Sapir said the ETF would expose bitcoin to a wider range of investors without the hassle of setting up accounts with cryptocurrency providers.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Ian Balina, the CEO of Token Metrics, stated that SEC approval of the ETF was a significant endorsement for the crypto industry because many regulators globally were not in favor of crypto, and retail investors were hesitant to accept crypto.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] This event would eventually open more opportunities for new capital and new people in this space.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The Department of the Treasury, on 20 May 2021, announced that it would require any transfer worth $10,000 or more to be reported to the Internal Revenue Service since cryptocurrency already posed a problem where illegal activity like tax evasion was facilitated broadly.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] This release from the IRS was a part of efforts to promote better compliance and consider more severe penalties for tax evaders.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] On 17 February 2022, the Department of Justice named Eun Young Choi as the first director of a National Cryptocurrency Enforcement Team to help identify and deal with misuse of cryptocurrencies and other digital assets.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The Biden administration faced a dilemma as it tried to develop regulations for the cryptocurrency industry.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] On one hand, officials were hesitant to restrict a growing industry.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] On the other hand, they were committed to preventing illegal cryptocurrency transactions.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] To reconcile these conflicting goals, on 9 March 2022, Biden issued an executive order.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Followed this, on 16 September 2022, the Comprehensive Framework for Responsible Development of Digital Assets document was released to support development of cryptocurrencies and restrict their illegal use.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The executive order included all digital assets, but cryptocurrencies posed both the greatest security risks and potential economic benefits.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] Though this might not address all of the challenges in crypto industry, it was a significant milestone in the US cryptocurrency regulation history.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In February 2023, the SEC ruled that cryptocurrency exchange Kraken's estimated $42 billion in staked assets globally operated as an illegal securities seller.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The company agreed to a $30 million settlement with the SEC and to cease selling its staking service in the US.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The case would impact other major crypto exchanges operating staking programs.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] On 23 March 2023, the SEC issued an alert to investors stating that firms offering crypto asset securities might not be complying with US laws.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] The SEC argued that unregistered offerings of crypto asset securities might not include important information.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p01] In addition the order prohibits the establishment, issuance or promotion of Central bank digital currency and establishes a group tasked with proposing a federal regulatory framework for digital assets within 180 days.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] The legal status of cryptocurrencies varies substantially from country to country and is still undefined or changing in many of them.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] At least one study has shown that broad generalizations about the use of bitcoin in illicit finance are significantly overstated and that blockchain analysis is an effective crime fighting and intelligence gathering tool.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] While some countries have explicitly allowed their use and trade, others have banned or restricted it.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] According to the Library of Congress in 2021, an "absolute ban" on trading or using cryptocurrencies applies in 9 countries: Algeria, Bangladesh, Bolivia, China, Egypt, Iraq, Morocco, Nepal, and the United Arab Emirates.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In the United States and Canada, state and provincial securities regulators, coordinated through the North American Securities Administrators Association, are investigating "Bitcoin scams" and ICOs in 40 jurisdictions.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Various government agencies, departments, and courts have classified bitcoin differently.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] China Central Bank banned the handling of bitcoins by financial institutions in China in early 2014.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In Russia, though owning cryptocurrency is legal, its residents are only allowed to purchase goods from other residents using the Russian ruble while nonresidents are allowed to use foreign currency.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Regulations and bans that apply to bitcoin probably extend to similar cryptocurrency systems.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In August 2018, the Bank of Thailand announced its plans to create its own cryptocurrency, the Central Bank Digital Currency (CBDC).
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In March 2014, the United States Internal Revenue Service (IRS) ruled that bitcoin will be treated as property for tax purposes.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Therefore, virtual currencies are considered commodities subject to capital gains tax.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] As the popularity and demand for cryptocurrencies has increased, so have concerns that they offer an unregulated person-to-person global economy that may become a threat to society.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Concerns abound that they may become tools for anonymous web criminals.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Cryptocurrency networks display a lack of regulation that has been criticized as enabling criminals who seek to evade taxes and launder money.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Money laundering issues are also present in regular bank transfers, however with bank-to-bank wire transfers for instance, the account holder must provide a proven identity.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Transactions that occur through the use and exchange of these cryptocurrencies are independent from formal banking systems, and therefore can make tax evasion simpler for individuals.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Since charting taxable income is based upon what a recipient reports to the revenue service, it becomes extremely difficult to account for transactions made using cryptocurrencies, a mode of exchange that is complex and difficult to track.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Systems of anonymity that most cryptocurrencies offer can also serve as a means to launder money.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Rather than laundering money through an intricate network of financial actors and offshore bank accounts, laundering money through cryptocurrencies can be achieved through anonymous transactions.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Cryptocurrency makes legal enforcement against extremist groups more complicated, which consequently strengthens them.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] White supremacist Richard Spencer declared bitcoin the "currency of the alt-right".
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In February 2014, the world's largest bitcoin exchange, Mt.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Likely due to theft, the company claimed that it had lost nearly 750,000 bitcoins belonging to their clients.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] This added up to approximately 7% of all bitcoins in existence, worth a total of $473 million.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Gox blamed hackers, who had exploited the transaction malleability problems in the network.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] The price of a bitcoin fell from a high of about $1,160 in December to under $400 in February.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] On 21 November 2017, Tether announced that it had been hacked, losing $31 million in USDT from its core treasury wallet.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] On 7 December 2017, Slovenian cryptocurrency exchange Nicehash reported that hackers had stolen over $70 million using a hijacked company computer.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] On 19 December 2017, Yapian, the owner of South Korean exchange Youbit, filed for bankruptcy after suffering two hacks that year.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Customers were still granted access to 75% of their assets.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In May 2018, Bitcoin Gold had its transactions hijacked and abused by unknown hackers.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Exchanges lost an estimated $18m and bitcoin Gold was delisted from Bittrex after it refused to pay its share of the damages.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] On 13 September 2018, Homero Josh Garza was sentenced to 21 months of imprisonment, followed by three years of supervised release.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Garza had founded the cryptocurrency startups GAW Miners and ZenMiner in 2014, acknowledged in a plea agreement that the companies were part of a pyramid scheme, and pleaded guilty to wire fraud in 2015.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] The SEC separately brought a civil enforcement action in the US against Garza, who was eventually ordered to pay a judgment of $9.1 million plus $700,000 in interest.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] The SEC's complaint stated that Garza, through his companies, had fraudulently sold "investment contracts representing shares in the profits they claimed would be generated" from mining.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In January 2018, Japanese exchange Coincheck reported that hackers had stolen cryptocurrency worth $530 million.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In June 2018, South Korean exchange Coinrail was hacked, losing over $37 million in crypto.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] The hack worsened a cryptocurrency selloff by an additional $42 billion.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] On 9 July 2018, the exchange Bancor, whose code and fundraising had been subjects of controversy, had $23.5 million in crypto stolen.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] A 2020 EU report found that users had lost crypto-assets worth hundreds of millions of US dollars in security breaches at exchanges and storage providers.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Between 2011 and 2019, reported breaches ranged from four to twelve a year.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2019, more than a billion dollars' worth of cryptoassets was reported stolen.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Stolen assets "typically find their way to illegal markets and are used to fund further criminal activity".
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] According to the UK 2020 national risk assessment—a comprehensive assessment of money laundering and terrorist financing risk in the UK—the risk of using cryptoassets such as bitcoin for money laundering and terrorism financing is assessed as "medium" (from "low" in the previous 2017 report).
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Legal scholars suggested that the money laundering opportunities may be more perceived than real.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Blockchain analysis company Chainalysis concluded that illicit activities like cybercrime, money laundering and terrorism financing made up only 0.15% of all crypto transactions conducted in 2021, representing a total of $14 billion.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In December 2021, Monkey Kingdom, a NFT project based in Hong Kong, lost US$1.3 million worth of cryptocurrencies via a phishing link used by the hacker.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] On 2 November 2023, Sam Bankman-Fried was pronounced guilty on seven counts of fraud related to FTX.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Federal criminal court sentencing experts speculated on the potential amount of prison time likely to be meted out.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] On 28 March 2024, the court sentenced Bankman-Fried to 25 years in prison.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] According to blockchain data company Chainalysis, criminals laundered $8.6 billion worth of cryptocurrency in 2021, up 30% from the previous year.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] The data suggests that rather than managing numerous illicit havens, cybercriminals make use of a small group of purpose-built centralized exchanges for sending and receiving illicit cryptocurrency.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2021, those exchanges received 47% of funds sent by crime-linked addresses.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Almost $2.2 billion worth of cryptocurrencies was embezzled from decentralized finance protocols in 2021, which represents 72% of all cryptocurrency theft in 2021.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Notable businesses include Garantex, Eggchange, Cashbank, Buy-Bitcoin, Tetchange, Bitzlato, and Suex, which was sanctioned by the U.S. in 2021.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Bitzlato founder and owner Anatoly Legkodymov was arrested following money-laundering charges by the United States Department of Justice.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Dark money has also been flowing into Russia through a dark web marketplace called Hydra, which is powered by cryptocurrency, and enjoyed more than $1 billion in sales in 2020, according to Chainalysis.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] The platform demands that sellers liquidate cryptocurrency only through certain regional exchanges, which has made it difficult for investigators to trace the money.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Almost 74% of ransomware revenue in 2021 — over $400 million worth of cryptocurrency — went to software strains likely affiliated with Russia, where oversight is notoriously limited.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2022, RenBridge—an unregulated alternative to exchanges for transferring value between blockchains—was found to be responsible for the laundering of at least $540 million since 2020.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] It is especially popular with people attempting to launder money from theft.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] This includes a cyberattack on Japanese crypto exchange Liquid that has been linked to North Korea.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Properties of cryptocurrencies gave them popularity in applications such as a safe haven in banking crises and means of payment, which also led to the cryptocurrency use in controversial settings in the form of online black markets, such as Silk Road.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] The original Silk Road was shut down in October 2013 and there have been two more versions in use since then.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In the year following the initial shutdown of Silk Road, the number of prominent dark markets increased from four to twelve, while the amount of drug listings increased from 18,000 to 32,000.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Darknet markets present challenges in regard to their legality.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Cryptocurrency used in dark markets are not clearly or legally classified in almost all parts of the world.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In the US, bitcoins are regarded as "virtual assets".
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] This type of ambiguous classification puts pressure on law enforcement agencies around the world to adapt to the shifting drug trade of dark markets.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Various studies have found that crypto-trading is rife with wash trading, a process, illegal in some jurisdictions, involving buyers and sellers being the same person or group, and which may be used to manipulate the price of a cryptocurrency or inflate volume artificially.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Exchanges with higher volumes can demand higher premiums from token issuers.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] A study from 2019 concluded that up to 80% of trades on unregulated cryptocurrency exchanges could be wash trades.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] A 2019 report by Bitwise Asset Management claimed that 95% of all bitcoin trading volume reported on major website CoinMarketCap had been artificially generated, and of 81 exchanges studied, only 10 provided legitimate volume figures.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2022, cryptocurrencies attracted attention when Western nations imposed severe economic sanctions on Russia in the aftermath of its invasion of Ukraine in February.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] However, American sources warned in March that some crypto-transactions could potentially be used to evade economic sanctions against Russia and Belarus.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In April 2022, the computer programmer Virgil Griffith received a five-year prison sentence in the US for attending a Pyongyang cryptocurrency conference, where he gave a presentation on blockchains which might be used for sanctions evasion.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] The Bank for International Settlements summarized several criticisms of cryptocurrencies in Chapter V of their 2018 annual report.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] The criticisms include the lack of stability in their price, the high energy consumption, high and variable transactions costs, the poor security and fraud at cryptocurrency exchanges, vulnerability to debasement (from forking), and the influence of miners.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Cryptocurrencies have been compared to Ponzi schemes, pyramid schemes and economic bubbles, such as housing market bubbles.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Regulators in several countries have warned against cryptocurrency and some have taken measures to dissuade users.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] However, research in 2021 by the UK's financial regulator suggests such warnings either went unheard, or were ignored.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Fewer than one in 10 potential cryptocurrency buyers were aware of consumer warnings on the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) website, and 12% of crypto users were not aware that their holdings were not protected by statutory compensation.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Of 1,000 respondents between the ages of eighteen and forty, 70% wrongly assumed cryptocurrencies were regulated, 75% of younger crypto investors claimed to be driven by competition with friends and family, and 58% said that social media enticed them to make high risk investments.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] The FCA recommends making use of its warning list, which flags unauthorized financial firms.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Many banks do not offer virtual currency services themselves and can refuse to do business with virtual currency companies.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2014, Gareth Murphy, a senior banking officer, suggested that the widespread adoption of cryptocurrencies may lead to too much money being obfuscated, blinding economists who would use such information to better steer the economy.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] While traditional financial products have strong consumer protections in place, there is no intermediary with the power to limit consumer losses if bitcoins are lost or stolen.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] One of the features cryptocurrency lacks in comparison to credit cards, for example, is consumer protection against fraud, such as chargebacks.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] The French regulator Autorité des marchés financiers (AMF) lists 16 websites of companies that solicit investment in cryptocurrency without being authorized to do so in France.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] An October 2021 paper by the National Bureau of Economic Research found that bitcoin suffers from systemic risk as the top 10,000 addresses control about one-third of all bitcoin in circulation.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] It is even worse for miners, with 0.01% controlling 50% of the capacity.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] According to researcher Flipside Crypto, less than 2% of anonymous accounts control 95% of all available bitcoin supply.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] This is considered risky as a great deal of the market is in the hands of a few entities.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] A paper by John Griffin, a finance professor at the University of Texas, and Amin Shams, a graduate student, found that in 2017 the price of bitcoin had been substantially inflated using another cryptocurrency, Tether.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Roger Lowenstein, author of "*Bank of America: The Epic Struggle to Create the Federal Reserve,*" said in a 2022 New York Times story that FTX currency exchange will face over $8 billion in claims.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Non-fungible tokens (NFTs) are digital assets that represent art, collectibles, gaming, etc.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Like crypto, their data is stored on the blockchain.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] NFTs are bought and traded using cryptocurrency.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] The Ethereum blockchain was the first place where NFTs were implemented, but now many other blockchains have created their own versions of NFTs.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] According to Vanessa Grellet, renowned panelist in blockchain conferences, there was an increasing interest from traditional stock exchanges in crypto-assets at the end of the 2010s, while crypto-exchanges such as Coinbase were gradually entering the traditional financial markets.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] This convergence marked a significant trend where conventional financial actors were adopting blockchain technology to enhance operational efficiency, while the crypto world introduced innovations like Security Token Offering (STO), enabling new ways of fundraising.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Tokenization, turning assets such as real estate, investment funds, and private equity into blockchain-based tokens, had the potential to make traditionally illiquid assets more accessible to investors.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Despite the regulatory risks associated with such developments, major financial institutions, including JPMorgan Chase, were actively working on blockchain initiatives, exemplified by the creation of Quorum, a private blockchain platform.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] As the first big Wall Street bank to embrace cryptocurrencies, Morgan Stanley announced on 17 March 2021 that they will be offering access to bitcoin funds for their wealthy clients through three funds which enable bitcoin ownership for investors with an aggressive risk tolerance.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] BNY Mellon on 11 February 2021 announced that it would begin offering cryptocurrency services to its clients.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] On 20 April 2021, Venmo added support to its platform to enable customers to buy, hold and sell cryptocurrencies.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In October 2021, financial services company Mastercard announced it is working with digital asset manager Bakkt on a platform that would allow any bank or merchant on the Mastercard network to offer cryptocurrency services.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Mining for proof-of-work (PoW) cryptocurrencies requires enormous amounts of electricity and consequently comes with a large carbon footprint due to causing greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Proof-of-work blockchains such as bitcoin, Ethereum, Litecoin, and Monero were estimated to have added between 3 million and 15 million tons of carbon dioxide (CO2) to the atmosphere in the period from 1 January 2016 to 30 June 2017.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] By November 2018, bitcoin was estimated to have an annual energy consumption of 45.8TWh, generating 22.0 to 22.9 million tons of CO2, rivalling nations like Jordan and Sri Lanka.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] By the end of 2021, bitcoin was estimated to produce 65.4 million tons of CO2, as much as Greece, and consume between 91 and 177 terawatt-hours annually.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Critics have also identified a large electronic waste problem in disposing of mining rigs.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Mining hardware is improving at a fast rate, quickly resulting in older generations of hardware.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Bitcoin is the least energy-efficient cryptocurrency, using 707.6 kilowatt-hours of electricity per transaction.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Before June 2021, China was the primary location for bitcoin mining.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] However, due to concerns over power usage and other factors, China forced out bitcoin operations, at least temporarily.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] As a result, the United States promptly emerged as the top global leader in the industry.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] An example of a gross amount of electronic waste associated with bitcoin mining operations in the US is a facility located in Dalton, Georgia which is consuming nearly the same amount of electricity as the combined power usage of 97,000 households in its vicinity.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Another example is that Riot Platforms operates a bitcoin mining facility in Rockdale, Texas, which consumes approximately as much electricity as the nearby 300,000 households.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] This makes it the most energy-intensive bitcoin mining operation in the United States.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] The world's second-largest cryptocurrency, Ethereum, uses 62.56 kilowatt-hours of electricity per transaction.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] XRP is the world's most energy efficient cryptocurrency, using 0.0079 kilowatt-hours of electricity per transaction.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Although the biggest PoW blockchains consume energy on the scale of medium-sized countries, the annual power demand from proof-of-stake (PoS) blockchains is on a scale equivalent to a housing estate.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] *The Times* identified six "environmentally friendly" cryptocurrencies: Bitgreen, Cardano, Chia, IOTA, Nano, and Solarcoin.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Academics and researchers have used various methods for estimating the energy use and energy efficiency of blockchains.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] This equates to Polkadot consuming 7 times the electricity of an average U.S. home, Cardano 57 homes and Solana 200 times as much.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] The research concluded that PoS networks consumed 0.001% the electricity of the bitcoin network.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] University College London researchers reached a similar conclusion.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Variable renewable energy power stations could invest in bitcoin mining to reduce curtailment, hedge electricity price risk, stabilize the grid, increase the profitability of renewable energy power stations and therefore accelerate transition to sustainable energy.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] There are also purely technical elements in play.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] For example, technological advancement in cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin result in high up-front costs to miners in the form of specialized hardware and software.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Cryptocurrency transactions are normally irreversible after a number of blocks confirm the transaction.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Additionally, cryptocurrency private keys can be permanently lost from local storage due to malware, data loss, or simply carelessness.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] This precludes the cryptocurrency from any usage whatsoever, permanently, thus removing it from the market.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In September 2015, the establishment of the peer-reviewed academic journal *Ledger* (ISSN 2379-5980) was announced.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] It covers studies of cryptocurrencies and related technologies, and is published by the University of Pittsburgh.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] The journal encourages authors to digitally sign a file hash of submitted papers, which will then be timestamped into the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Authors are also asked to include a personal bitcoin address in the first page of their papers.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] A number of aid agencies have started accepting donations in cryptocurrencies, including UNICEF.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Christopher Fabian, principal adviser at UNICEF Innovation, said the children's fund would uphold donor protocols, meaning that people making donations online would have to pass checks before they were allowed to deposit funds.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] However, in 2021, there was a backlash against donations in bitcoin because of the environmental emissions it caused.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Some agencies stopped accepting bitcoin and others turned to "greener" cryptocurrencies.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] The U.S. arm of Greenpeace stopped accepting bitcoin donations after seven years.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2022, the Ukrainian government raised over US$10,000,000 worth of aid through cryptocurrency following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Bitcoin was characterized as a speculative bubble in 2014–2018 by eight winners of the Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences: Angus Deaton, Oliver Hart, James Heckman, Paul Krugman, Thomas Sargent, Robert J.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Shiller, Joseph Stiglitz, and Richard Thaler; and in 2013–2018 by central bank officials including Agustín Carstens (Mexico), Vítor Constâncio (Portugal), Alan Greenspan (US), and Nout Wellink (Netherlands).
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Investors Warren Buffett and George Soros have respectively characterized it in 2014–2018 as a "mirage" and a "bubble".
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Business executives Jack Ma and JP Morgan Chase CEO Jamie Dimon have called it in 2017–2018 a "bubble" and a "fraud", respectively, although Jamie Dimon later said in 2018 that he regretted stating bitcoin was a fraud.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Fink in 2017 called bitcoin an "index of money laundering".
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In June 2022, business magnate Bill Gates said that cryptocurrencies are "100% based on greater fool theory".
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Legal scholars criticize the lack of regulation, which hinders conflict resolution when crypto assets are at the center of a legal dispute, for example a divorce or an inheritance.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In Switzerland, jurists generally deny that cryptocurrencies are objects that fall under property law, as cryptocurrencies do not belong to any class of legally defined objects (*Typenzwang*, the legal numerus clausus).
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Therefore, it is debated whether anybody could even be sued for embezzlement of cryptocurrency if they had access to someone's wallet.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] However, in the law of obligations and contract law, any kind of object would be legally valid, but the object would have to be tied to an identified counterparty.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] However, inasmuch the more popular cryptocurrencies can be freely and quickly exchanged into legal tender, they are financial assets and have to be taxed and accounted for as such.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] Losses associated with cryptocurrency investments have been linked to suicides.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2018, an increase in crypto-related suicides was noticed after the cryptocurrency market crashed in August.
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] The situation was particularly critical in Korea as crypto traders were on "suicide watch".
[src:monero-privacy/cryptocurrency-p02] The May 2022 collapse of the Luna currency operated by Terra also led to reports of suicidal investors in crypto-related subreddits.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Digital currencies exhibit properties similar to traditional currencies, but generally do not have a classical physical form of fiat currency historically that can be held in the hand, like currencies with printed banknotes or minted coins.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] However, they do have a physical form in an unclassical sense coming from the computer to computer and computer to human interactions and the information and processing power of the servers that store and keep track of money.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] This unclassical physical form allows nearly instantaneous transactions over the internet and vastly lowers the cost associated with distributing notes and coins: for example, of the types of money in the UK economy, 3% are notes and coins, and 79% as electronic money (in the form of bank deposits).
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Usually not issued by a governmental body, virtual currencies are not considered a legal tender and they enable ownership transfer across governmental borders.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] This type of currency may be used to buy physical goods and services, but may also be restricted to certain communities such as for use inside an online game.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Digital money can either be centralized, where there is a central point of control over the money supply (for instance, a bank), or decentralized, where the control over the money supply is predetermined or agreed upon democratically.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Precursory ideas for digital currencies were presented in electronic payment methods such as the Sabre (travel reservation system).
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In 1983, a research paper titled "Blind Signatures for Untraceable Payments" by David Chaum introduced the idea of digital cash.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In 1989, he founded DigiCash, an electronic cash company, in Amsterdam to commercialize the ideas in his research.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] e-gold was the first widely used Internet money, introduced in 1996, and grew to several million users before the US Government shut it down in 2008. e-gold has been referenced to as "digital currency" by both US officials and academia.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In 1997, Coca-Cola offered buying from vending machines using mobile payments.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] PayPal launched its USD-denominated service in 1998.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In 2009, bitcoin was launched, which marked the start of decentralized blockchain-based digital currencies with no central server, and no tangible assets held in reserve.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Also known as cryptocurrencies, blockchain-based digital currencies proved resistant to attempt by government to regulate them, because there was no central organization or person with the power to turn them off.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Origins of digital currencies date back to the 1990s Dot-com bubble.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Another known digital currency service was Liberty Reserve, founded in 2006; it lets users convert dollars or euros to Liberty Reserve Dollars or Euros, and exchange them freely with one another at a 1% fee.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Several digital currency operations were reputed to be used for Ponzi schemes and money laundering, and were prosecuted by the U.S. government for operating without MSB licenses.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Q coins or QQ coins, were used as a type of commodity-based digital currency on Tencent QQ's messaging platform and emerged in early 2005.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Q coins were so effective in China that they were said to have had a destabilizing effect on the Chinese yuan currency due to speculation.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Recent interest in cryptocurrencies has prompted renewed interest in digital currencies, with bitcoin, introduced in 2008, becoming the most widely used and accepted digital currency.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Digital currency is a term that refers to a specific type of electronic currency with specific properties.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Digital currency is also a term used to include the meta-group of sub-types of digital currency, the specific meaning can only be determined within the specific legal or contextual case.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Legally and technically, there already are a myriad of legal definitions of digital currency and the many digital currency sub-types.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Combining different possible properties, there exists an extensive number of implementations creating many and numerous sub-types of digital currency.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Many governmental jurisdictions have implemented their own unique definition for digital currency, virtual currency, cryptocurrency, e-money, network money, e-cash, and other types of digital currency.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Within any specific government jurisdiction, different agencies and regulators define different and often conflicting meanings for the different types of digital currency based on the specific properties of a specific currency type or sub-type.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] A virtual currency has been defined in 2012 by the European Central Bank as "a type of unregulated, digital money, which is issued and usually controlled by its developers, and used and accepted among the members of a specific virtual community".
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The US Department of Treasury in 2013 defined it more tersely as "a medium of exchange that operates like a currency in some environments, but does not have all the attributes of real currency".
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] According to the European Central Bank's 2015 "Virtual currency schemes – a further analysis" report, virtual currency is a digital representation of value, not issued by a central bank, credit institution or e-money institution, which, in some circumstances, can be used as an alternative to money.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In the previous report of October 2012, the virtual currency was defined as a type of unregulated, digital money, which is issued and usually controlled by its developers, and used and accepted among the members of a specific virtual community.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] According to the Bank for International Settlements' November 2015 "Digital currencies" report, it is an asset represented in digital form and having some monetary characteristics.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Digital currency can be denominated to a sovereign currency and issued by the issuer responsible to redeem digital money for cash.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In that case, digital currency represents electronic money (e-money).
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Digital currency denominated in its own units of value or with decentralized or automatic issuance will be considered as a virtual currency.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] As such, bitcoin is a digital currency but also a type of virtual currency. bitcoin and its alternatives are based on cryptographic algorithms, so these kinds of virtual currencies are also called cryptocurrencies.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Cryptocurrency is a sub-type of digital currency and a digital asset that relies on cryptography to chain together digital signatures of asset transfers, peer-to-peer networking and decentralization.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In some cases a proof-of-work or proof-of-stake scheme is used to create and manage the currency.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Cryptocurrencies can allow electronic money systems to be decentralized.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] When implemented with a blockchain, the digital ledger system or record keeping system uses cryptography to edit separate shards of database entries that are distributed across many separate servers.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The first and most popular system is bitcoin, a peer-to-peer electronic monetary system based on cryptography.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Most of the traditional money supply is bank money held on computers.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] They are considered digital currency in some cases.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] One could argue that our increasingly cashless society means that all currencies are becoming digital currencies, but they are not presented to us as such.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Currency can be exchanged electronically using debit cards and credit cards using electronic funds transfer at point of sale.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] A number of electronic money systems use contactless payment transfer in order to facilitate easy payment and give the payee more confidence in not letting go of their electronic wallet during the transaction.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] A central bank digital currency (CBDC) is a form of universally accessible digital money in a nation and holds the same value as the country's paper currency.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Like a cryptocurrency, a CBDC is held in the form of tokens.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] CBDCs are different from regular digital cash forms like in online bank accounts because CBDCs are established through the central bank within a country, with liabilities held by one's government, rather than from a commercial bank.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Approximately nine countries have already established a CBDC, with interest in the system increasing highly throughout the world.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In these nations, CBDCs have been used as a form of exchange and a way for governments to try to prevent risks from occurring within their financial systems.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] A major problem with central bank digital currencies is deciding whether the currency should be easily trackable.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] If it's traceable, the government has more control than it currently does.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Additionally, there's a technical aspect to consider: whether CBDCs should be based on tokens or accounts and how much anonymity users should have.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Digital Currency has been implemented in some cases as a decentralized system of any combination of currency issuance, ownership record, ownership transfer authorization and validation, and currency storage.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Per the Bank for International Settlements (BIS), "These schemes do not distinguish between users based on location, and therefore allow value to be transferred between users across borders.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Since 2001, the European Union has implemented the E-Money Directive "on the taking up, pursuit and prudential supervision of the business of electronic money institutions" last amended in 2009.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In the United States, electronic money is governed by Article 4A of the Uniform Commercial Code for wholesale transactions and the Electronic Fund Transfer Act for consumer transactions.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Provider's responsibility and consumer's liability are regulated under Regulation E.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Virtual currencies pose challenges for central banks, financial regulators, departments or ministries of finance, as well as fiscal authorities and statistical authorities.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] As of 2016, over 24 countries are investing in distributed ledger technologies (DLT) with $1.4bn in investments.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In addition, over 90 central banks are engaged in DLT discussions, including implications of a central bank issued digital currency.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In March 2018, the Marshall Islands became the first country to issue their own cryptocurrency and certify it as legal tender; the currency is called the "sovereign".
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The US Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC) has determined virtual currencies are properly defined as commodities in 2015.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The CFTC warned investors against pump and dump schemes that use virtual currencies.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The US Internal Revenue Service (IRS) ruling Notice 2014-21 defines any virtual currency, cryptocurrency and digital currency as property; gains and losses are taxable within standard property policies.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] On 20 March 2013, the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network issued a guidance to clarify how the U.S.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Bank Secrecy Act applied to persons creating, exchanging, and transmitting virtual currencies.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In May 2014 the US Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) "warned about the hazards of bitcoin and other virtual currencies".
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In July 2014, the New York State Department of Financial Services proposed the most comprehensive regulation of virtual currencies to date, commonly called BitLicense.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] It has gathered input from bitcoin supporters and the financial industry through public hearings and a comment period until 21 October 2014 to customize the rules.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The proposal per NY DFS press release "sought to strike an appropriate balance that helps protect consumers and root out illegal activity".
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] It has been criticized by smaller companies to favor established institutions, and Chinese bitcoin exchanges have complained that the rules are "overly broad in its application outside the United States".
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The Bank of Canada has explored the possibility of creating a version of its currency on the blockchain.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The Bank of Canada teamed up with the nation's five largest banks – and the blockchain consulting firm R3 – for what was known as Project Jasper.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In a simulation run in 2016, the central bank issued CAD-Coins onto a blockchain similar Ethereum.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The banks used the CAD-Coins to exchange money the way they do at the end of each day to settle their master accounts.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In 2016, Fan Yifei, a deputy governor of China's central bank, the People's Bank of China (PBOC), wrote that "the conditions are ripe for digital currencies, which can reduce operating costs, increase efficiency and enable a wide range of new applications".
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] According to Fan Yifei, the best way to take advantage of the situation is for central banks to take the lead, both in supervising private digital currencies and in developing digital legal tender of their own.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In October 2019, the PBOC announced that a digital renminbi would be released after years of preparation.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The version of the currency, known as DCEP (Digital Currency Electronic Payment), is based on cryptocurrency which can be "decoupled" from the banking system.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The announcement received a variety of responses: some believe it is more about domestic control and surveillance.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In December 2020, the PBOC distributed CN¥20 million worth of digital renminbi to the residents of Suzhou through a lottery program to further promote the government-backed digital currency.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Recipients of the currency could make both offline and online purchases, expanding on an earlier trial that did not require internet connection through the inclusion of online stores in the program.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Around 20,000 transactions were reported by the e-commerce company JD.com in the first 24 hours of the trial.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Contrary to other online payment platforms such as Alipay or WeChat Pay, the digital currency does not have transaction fees.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The Danish government proposed getting rid of the obligation for selected retailers to accept payment in cash, moving the country closer to a "cashless" economy.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The Danish Chamber of Commerce is backing the move.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Nearly a third of the Danish population uses MobilePay, a smartphone application for transferring money.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] A law passed by the National Assembly of Ecuador gives the government permission to make payments in electronic currency and proposes the creation of a national digital currency.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] "Electronic money will stimulate the economy; it will be possible to attract more Ecuadorian citizens, especially those who do not have checking or savings accounts and credit cards alone.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The electronic currency will be backed by the assets of the Central Bank of Ecuador", the National Assembly said in a statement.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In December 2015, Sistema de Dinero Electrónico ("electronic money system") was launched, making Ecuador the first country with a state-run electronic payment system.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] On 9 June 2021, the Legislative Assembly of El Salvador has become the first country in the world to officially classify bitcoin as legal currency.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Starting 90 days after approval, every business must accept bitcoin as legal tender for goods or services, unless it is unable to provide the technology needed to do the transaction.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The Dutch central bank is experimenting with a blockchain-based virtual currency called "DNBCoin".
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The Unified Payments Interface (UPI) is a real-time payment system for instant money transfers between any two bank accounts held in participating banks in India.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The interface has been developed by the National Payments Corporation of India and is regulated by the Reserve Bank of India.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] This digital payment system is available 24 hours a day, every day of the year.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] UPI is agnostic to the type of user and is used for person to person, person to business, business to person and business to business transactions.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Transactions can be initiated by the payer or the payee.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] To identify a bank account it uses a unique Virtual Payment Address (VPA) of the type 'accountID@bankID'.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The VPA can be assigned by the bank, but can also be self specified just like an email address.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The simplest and most common form of VPA is 'mobilenumber@upi'.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Money can be transferred from one VPA to another or from one VPA to any bank account in a participating bank using account number and bank branch details.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Transfers can be inter-bank or intra-bank.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] UPI has no intermediate holding pond for money.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] It withdraws funds directly from the bank account of the sender and deposits them directly into the recipient's bank account whenever a transaction is requested.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] A sender can initiate and authorise a transfer using a two step secure process: login using a pass code → initiate → verify using a passcode.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] A receiver can initiate a payment request on the system to send the payer a notification or by presenting a QR code.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] On receiving the request, the payer can decline or confirm the payment using the same two step process: login → confirm → verify.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The system is extraordinarily user friendly to the extent that even technophobes and barely literate users are adopting it in huge numbers.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Government-controlled Sberbank of Russia owns YooMoney – electronic payment service and digital currency of the same name.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Sweden completed the replacement of all physical banknotes and most coins by mid-2017.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] However, the new banknotes and coins of the Swedish krona will probably be circulating at about half the 2007 peak of 12,494 kronor per capita.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The Riksbank is planning to begin discussions of an electronic currency issued by the central bank to which "is not to replace cash, but to act as complement to it".
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Deputy Governor Cecilia Skingsley states that cash will continue to spiral out of use in Sweden, and while it is currently fairly easy to get cash in Sweden, it is often very difficult to deposit it into bank accounts, especially in rural areas.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] No decision has been currently made about the decision to create "e-krona".
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In 2016, a city government first accepted digital currency in payment of city fees.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Zug, Switzerland, added bitcoin as a means of paying small amounts, up to SFr 200, in a test and an attempt to advance Zug as a region that is advancing future technologies.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In order to reduce risk, Zug immediately converts any bitcoin received into the Swiss currency.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Swiss Federal Railways, government-owned railway company of Switzerland, sells bitcoins at its ticket machines.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In 2016, the UK's chief scientific adviser, Sir Mark Walport, advised the government to consider using a blockchain-based digital currency.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The chief economist of Bank of England, the central bank of the United Kingdom, proposed the abolition of paper currency.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The Bank has also taken an interest in blockchain.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] In 2016 it has embarked on a multi-year research programme to explore the implications of a central bank issued digital currency.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The Bank of England has produced several research papers on the topic.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] One suggests that the economic benefits of issuing a digital currency on a distributed ledger could add as much as 3 percent to a country's economic output.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The Bank said that it wanted the next version of the bank's basic software infrastructure to be compatible with distributed ledgers.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Government attitude dictates the tendency among established heavy financial actors that both are risk-averse and conservative.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] None of these offered services around cryptocurrencies and much of the criticism came from them.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] It will work with bitcoin and Ethereum with general availability scheduled for 2019.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Hard electronic currency does not have the ability to be disputed or reversed when used.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] It is nearly impossible to reverse a transaction, justified or not.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Contrarily, soft electronic currency payments can be reversed.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Usually, when a payment is reversed there is a "clearing time." A hard currency can be "softened" with a third-party service.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Many existing digital currencies have not yet seen widespread usage, and may not be easily used or exchanged.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Banks generally do not accept or offer services for them.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] There are concerns that cryptocurrencies are extremely risky due to their very high volatility and potential for pump and dump schemes.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Regulators in several countries have warned against their use and some have taken concrete regulatory measures to dissuade users.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The non-cryptocurrencies are all centralized.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] As such, they may be shut down or seized by a government at any time.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] The more anonymous a currency is, the more attractive it is to criminals, regardless of the intentions of its creators. bitcoin has also been criticised for its energy inefficient SHA-256-based proof of work.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] According to Barry Eichengreen, an economist known for his work on monetary and financial economics, "cryptocurrencies like bitcoin are too volatile to possess the essential attributes of money.
[src:monero-privacy/digital-currency] Stablecoins have fragile currency pegs that diminish their utility in transactions.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] The protocol is open source and based on CryptoNote v2, a concept described in a 2013 white paper authored by Nicolas van Saberhagen.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Developers used this concept to design Monero, and deployed its mainnet in 2014.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] The Monero protocol includes various methods to obfuscate transaction details, though users can optionally share view keys for third-party auditing.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Transactions are validated through a miner network running RandomX, a proof-of-work algorithm.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] The algorithm issues new coins to miners and was designed to be resistant against application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) mining.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Monero's privacy features have attracted cypherpunks and users desiring privacy measures not provided in other cryptocurrencies.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] A 2022 study in *FSI Digital Investigations* concluded "For now, Monero is untraceable.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] However, it is probably only a matter of time and effort before it changes." Due to its perceived untraceability Monero is gaining increased use in illicit activities such as money laundering, darknet markets, ransomware, cryptojacking, and other organized crime.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Monero's roots trace back to CryptoNote v2, a cryptocurrency protocol first introduced in a white paper published by the presumed pseudonymous Nicolas van Saberhagen in October 2013.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] In the paper, the author described privacy and anonymity as "the most important aspects of electronic cash" and characterized bitcoin's traceability as a "critical flaw".
[src:monero-privacy/monero] A Bitcointalk forum user known as "*thankful_for_today*" implemented these ideas into a coin they called BitMonero.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] However, other forum users disagreed with *thankful_for_today'*s direction for BitMonero and decided to fork it in 2014, leading to the creation of Monero.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] *Monero* translates to *coin* in Esperanto.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] The plural of monero ("moneroj") is likewise formed using Esperanto grammar.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Both van Saberhagen and *thankful_for_today* remain anonymous.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Monero has the third-largest community of developers, behind bitcoin and Ethereum.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] The protocol's lead maintainer was previously South African developer Riccardo Spagni.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Much of the core development team chooses to remain anonymous.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Monero's key features are those around privacy and anonymity.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Even though it is a public and decentralized ledger, all transaction details are obfuscated.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] This contrasts to bitcoin, where all transaction details, user addresses, and wallet balances are public and transparent.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] These features have given Monero a loyal following among crypto anarchists, cypherpunks, and privacy advocates.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] The transaction outputs, or notes, of users sending Monero are obfuscated through ring signatures, which groups a sender's outputs with other decoy outputs.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Encryption of transaction amounts began in 2017 with the implementation of ring confidential transactions (RingCTs).
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Developers also implemented a zero-knowledge proof method, "Bulletproofs", which guarantee a transaction occurred without revealing its value.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Monero recipients are protected through "stealth addresses", public keys generated by the sender that are untraceable to the receiver by a network observer.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] These privacy features are enforced on the network by default.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Monero uses Dandelion++, a protocol which obscures the IP address of devices producing transactions.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] In April 2017, researchers highlighted three major threats to Monero users' privacy.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] The first relies on leveraging the ring signature size of zero, and ability to see the output amounts.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] The second, "Leveraging Output Merging", involves tracking transactions where two outputs belong to the same user, such as when they send funds to themselves ("churning").
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Finally, "Temporal Analysis", shows that predicting the right output in a ring signature could potentially be easier than previously thought.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] In 2018, researchers presented possible vulnerabilities in a paper titled "An Empirical Analysis of Traceability in the Monero Blockchain".
[src:monero-privacy/monero] In September 2020, the United States Internal Revenue Service's criminal investigation division (IRS-CI), posted a $625,000 bounty for contractors who could develop tools to help trace Monero, other privacy-enhanced cryptocurrencies, the Bitcoin Lightning Network, or other "layer 2" protocol.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] The contract was awarded to blockchain analysis groups Chainalysis and Integra FEC.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] In 2021, researchers presented a transaction-flooding attack against Monero’s transaction-graph privacy at the IEEE International Conference on Blockchain and Cryptocurrency.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Under specific assumptions about transaction structure and fees, the "FloodXMR" attack modelled how an adversary who floods the blockchain with their own transactions could, over time, deanonymize a substantial fraction of new transaction inputs at relatively low cost.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Monero uses a proof-of-work algorithm, RandomX, to validate transactions.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] The method was introduced in November 2019 to replace the former algorithm CryptoNightR.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Both algorithms were designed to be resistant to ASIC mining, which is commonly used to mine other cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Monero's privacy features have made it popular for illicit purposes.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] On-chain data from 2024 and 2025 shows that Monero’s transaction volumes remained significantly higher than in the 2020–2021 period, stabilizing at an elevated baseline that indicates sustained, regular demand rather than temporary speculation.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] After a wave of cryptocurrency exchange delistings in 2024–2025, Monero trading migrated to decentralized and peer-to-peer platforms, demonstrating resilient usage and ongoing demand.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Monero's privacy features have made it the dominant cryptocurrency on darknet markets (DNMs), where anonymity is critical for both buyers and sellers.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Unlike Bitcoin, whose public ledger enables traceable blockchain analysis, Monero obscures sender, receiver, and transaction amounts by default.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] In August 2016, dark market AlphaBay permitted its vendors to start accepting Monero as an alternative to bitcoin.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] The site was taken offline by law enforcement in 2017, but it was relaunched in 2021 with Monero as the sole permitted currency.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] A 2024 report covered by *Wired* found that vendors of child sexual abuse material increasingly used Monero for laundering proceeds through instant exchangers, with blockchain analysis firm Chainalysis describing Monero as "the currency of choice" for this purpose.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] By 2025, nearly half of newly launched darknet markets operated exclusively with Monero, a sharp increase from earlier years, driven by law enforcement advances in tracing Bitcoin and stablecoins.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] This trend has created a perception that markets relying solely on Bitcoin are less secure, pushing users toward Monero-only platforms that better protect against financial surveillance.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] A prominent example was White House Market, a darknet marketplace active from 2019 to 2021 that was used to traffic fentanyl and cocaine; the platform handled transactions in Monero and was referenced in multiple federal indictments.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] The market's closure did not halt the broader shift, as subsequent DNMs increasingly adopted Monero-only models that users deem more trustworthy because of the difficulty of tracing XMR payments.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] The United States Department of Justice and the Treasury Department have identified Monero as a frequently used tool in darknet and ransomware-related money laundering, with sanctioned exchangers processing hundreds of millions of dollars in XMR.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] In late 2017, malware and antivirus service providers blocked Coinhive, a JavaScript implementation of a Monero miner that was embedded in websites and apps, in some cases by hackers.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Coinhive wrote the script as an alternative to advertisements; a website or app could embed it, and use website visitors' CPU to mine the cryptocurrency while the visitor is consuming the content of the webpage, with the site or app owner getting a percentage of the mined coins.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Some websites and apps did this without informing visitors, or in some cases using all possible system resources.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] As a result, the script was blocked by companies offering ad blocking subscription lists, antivirus services, and antimalware services.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Coinhive had been previously found hidden in *Showtime-*owned streaming platforms and Starbucks Wi-Fi hotspots in Argentina.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Researchers in 2018 found similar malware that mined Monero and sent it to Kim Il-sung University in North Korea.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Monero is sometimes used by ransomware groups.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] According to CNBC, in the first half of 2018, Monero was used in 44% of cryptocurrency ransomware attacks.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] The perpetrators of the 2017 WannaCry ransomware attack, which was attributed by the US government to North Korean threat actors, attempted to exchange the ransom they collected in Bitcoin to Monero.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] *Ars Technica* and *Fast Company* reported that the exchange was successful, but BBC News reported that the service the criminals attempted to use, ShapeShift, denied any such transfer.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] The Shadow Brokers, who leaked the exploits which were subsequently used in WannaCry but are unlikely to have been involved in the attack, began accepting Monero as payment later in 2017.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] In 2021, CNBC, the *Financial Times*, and *Newsweek* reported that demand for Monero was increasing following the recovery of a bitcoin ransom paid in the Colonial Pipeline cyber attack.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] The May 2021 hack forced the pipeline to pay a $4.4M ransom in bitcoin, though a large portion was recovered by the United States federal government the following month.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] The group behind the attack, DarkSide, normally requests payment in either bitcoin or Monero, but charge a 10–20% premium for payments made in bitcoin due to its increased traceability risk.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Ransomware group REvil removed the option of paying ransom in bitcoin in 2021, demanding only Monero.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Ransomware negotiators, groups that help victims pay ransoms, have contacted Monero developers to understand the technology.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Despite this, CNBC reported that bitcoin was still the currency of choice demanded in most ransomware attacks, as insurers refuse to pay Monero ransom payments because of traceability concerns.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] The attribution of Monero to illicit markets has influenced some exchanges to forgo listing it.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] This has made it more difficult for users to exchange Monero for fiat currencies or other cryptocurrencies.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] Exchanges in South Korea and Australia have delisted Monero and other privacy coins due to regulatory pressure.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] In 2018, Europol and its director Rob Wainwright wrote that the year would see criminals shift from using bitcoin to using Monero, as well as Ethereum, Dash, and Zcash.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] *Bloomberg* and CNN reported that this demand for Monero was because authorities were becoming better at monitoring the Bitcoin blockchain.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] On 20 February 2024, the cryptocurrency exchange Binance delisted Monero, citing regulatory compliance.
[src:monero-privacy/monero] The United States Internal Revenue Service (IRS) has offered funding for contractors that can develop Monero tracing technologies.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Public key algorithms are fundamental security primitives in modern cryptosystems, including applications and protocols that offer assurance of the confidentiality and authenticity of electronic communications and data storage.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] They underpin numerous Internet standards, such as Transport Layer Security (TLS), SSH, S/MIME, and PGP.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Compared to symmetric cryptography, public-key cryptography can be too slow for many purposes, so these protocols often combine symmetric cryptography with public-key cryptography in hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Before the mid-1970s, all cipher systems used symmetric key algorithms, in which the same cryptographic key is used with the underlying algorithm by both the sender and the recipient, who must both keep the key secret.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Of necessity, the key in every such system had to be exchanged between the communicating parties in some secure way prior to any use of the system – for instance, via a secure channel.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] This requirement is never trivial and very rapidly becomes unmanageable as the number of participants increases, when secure channels are not available, or when (as is sensible cryptographic practice) keys are frequently changed.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] In particular, if messages are meant to be secure from other users, a separate key is required for each possible pair of users.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] By contrast, in a public-key cryptosystem, the public keys can be disseminated widely and openly, and only the corresponding private keys need be kept secret.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] For example, a software publisher can create a signature key pair and include the public key in software installed on computers.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Later, the publisher can distribute an update to the software signed using the private key, and any computer receiving an update can confirm it is genuine by verifying the signature using the public key.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] As long as the software publisher keeps the private key secret, even if a forger can distribute malicious updates to computers, they cannot convince the computers that any malicious updates are genuine.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] For example, a journalist can publish the public key of an encryption key pair on a website so that sources can send secret messages to the news organization in ciphertext.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Only the journalist who knows the corresponding private key can decrypt the ciphertexts to obtain the sources' messages—an eavesdropper reading email on its way to the journalist cannot decrypt the ciphertexts.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] However, public-key encryption does not conceal metadata like what computer a source used to send a message, when they sent it, or how long it is.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Public-key encryption on its own also does not tell the recipient anything about who sent a message—it just conceals the content of the message.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Applications built on public-key cryptography include authenticating web servers with TLS, digital cash, password-authenticated key agreement, authenticating and concealing email content with OpenPGP or S/MIME, and time-stamping services and non-repudiation protocols.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] One important issue is confidence or proof that a particular public key is authentic, i.e., that it is correct and belongs to the person or entity claimed, and has not been tampered with or replaced by some (perhaps malicious) third party.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] A public key infrastructure (PKI), in which one or more third parties, known as certificate authorities, certify ownership of key pairs.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] This implies that the PKI system (software, hardware, and management) can be trusted by all involved.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] A web of trust decentralizes authentication by using individual endorsements of links between a user and their public key.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] PGP uses this approach, in addition to lookup in the domain name system (DNS).
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] The DKIM system for digitally signing emails also uses this approach.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] PGP, SSH, and the SSL/TLS family of schemes use this procedure; they are thus called hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] As with all security-related systems, there are various potential weaknesses in public-key cryptography.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Aside from poor choice of an asymmetric key algorithm (there are few that are widely regarded as satisfactory) or too short a key length, the chief security risk is that the private key of a pair becomes known.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] All security of messages, authentication, etc., encrypted with this private key will then be lost.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] This is commonly mitigated (such as in recent TLS schemes) by using Forward secrecy capable schemes that generate an ephemeral set of keys during the communication which must also be known for the communication to be compromised.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Additionally, with the advent of quantum computing, many asymmetric key algorithms are considered vulnerable to attacks, and new quantum-resistant schemes are being developed to overcome the problem.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Beyond algorithmic or key-length weaknesses, some studies have noted risks when private key control is delegated to third parties.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Research on Uruguay’s implementation of Public Key Infrastructure under Law 18.600 found that centralized key custody by Trust Service Providers (TSPs) may weaken the principle of private-key secrecy, increasing exposure to man-in-the-middle attacks and raising concerns about legal non-repudiation.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] All public key schemes are in theory susceptible to a "brute-force key search attack".
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] However, such an attack is impractical if the amount of computation needed to succeed – termed the "work factor" by Claude Shannon – is out of reach of all potential attackers.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] In many cases, the work factor can be increased by simply choosing a longer key.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] But other algorithms may inherently have much lower work factors, making resistance to a brute-force attack (e.g., from longer keys) irrelevant.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Some special and specific algorithms have been developed to aid in attacking some public key encryption algorithms; both RSA and ElGamal encryption have known attacks that are much faster than the brute-force approach.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] None of these are sufficiently improved to be actually practical, however.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Major weaknesses have been found for several formerly promising asymmetric key algorithms.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] The "knapsack packing" algorithm was found to be insecure after the development of a new attack.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] As with all cryptographic functions, public-key implementations may be vulnerable to side-channel attacks that exploit information leakage to simplify the search for a secret key.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] These are often independent of the algorithm being used.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Research is underway to both discover, and to protect against, new attacks.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Another potential security vulnerability in using asymmetric keys is the possibility of a "man-in-the-middle" attack, in which the communication of public keys is intercepted by a third party (the "man in the middle") and then modified to provide different public keys instead.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Encrypted messages and responses must, in all instances, be intercepted, decrypted, and re-encrypted by the attacker using the correct public keys for the different communication segments so as to avoid suspicion.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] A communication is said to be insecure where data is transmitted in a manner that allows for interception (also called "sniffing").
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] These terms refer to reading the sender's private data in its entirety.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] A communication is particularly unsafe when interceptions can not be prevented or monitored by the sender.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] A man-in-the-middle attack can be difficult to implement due to the complexities of modern security protocols.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] However, the task becomes simpler when a sender is using insecure media such as public networks, the Internet, or wireless communication.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] In these cases an attacker can compromise the communications infrastructure rather than the data itself.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] A hypothetical malicious staff member at an Internet service provider (ISP) might find a man-in-the-middle attack relatively straightforward.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Capturing the public key would only require searching for the key as it gets sent through the ISP's communications hardware; in properly implemented asymmetric key schemes, this is not a significant risk.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] In some advanced man-in-the-middle attacks, one side of the communication will see the original data while the other will receive a malicious variant.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Asymmetric man-in-the-middle attacks can prevent users from realizing their connection is compromised.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] This remains so even when one user's data is known to be compromised because the data appears fine to the other user.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] This can lead to confusing disagreements between users such as "it must be on your end!" when neither user is at fault.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Hence, man-in-the-middle attacks are only fully preventable when the communications infrastructure is physically controlled by one or both parties; such as via a wired route inside the sender's own building.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] In summation, public keys are easier to alter when the communications hardware used by a sender is controlled by an attacker.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] One approach to prevent such attacks involves the use of a public key infrastructure (PKI); a set of roles, policies, and procedures needed to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key encryption.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Web browsers, for instance, are supplied with a long list of "self-signed identity certificates" from PKI providers – these are used to check the *bona fides* of the certificate authority and then, in a second step, the certificates of potential communicators.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who could subvert one of those certificate authorities into issuing a certificate for a bogus public key could then mount a "man-in-the-middle" attack as easily as if the certificate scheme were not used at all.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who penetrates an authority's servers and obtains its store of certificates and keys (public and private) would be able to spoof, masquerade, decrypt, and forge transactions without limit, assuming that they were able to place themselves in the communication stream.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Despite its theoretical and potential problems, Public key infrastructure is widely used.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Examples include TLS and its predecessor SSL, which are commonly used to provide security for web browser transactions (for example, most websites utilize TLS for HTTPS).
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Aside from the resistance to attack of a particular key pair, the security of the certification hierarchy must be considered when deploying public key systems.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Some certificate authority – usually a purpose-built program running on a server computer – vouches for the identities assigned to specific private keys by producing a digital certificate.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Public key digital certificates are typically valid for several years at a time, so the associated private keys must be held securely over that time.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] When a private key used for certificate creation higher in the PKI server hierarchy is compromised, or accidentally disclosed, then a "man-in-the-middle attack" is possible, making any subordinate certificate wholly insecure.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Most of the available public-key encryption software does not conceal metadata in the message header, which might include the identities of the sender and recipient, the sending date, subject field, and the software they use etc.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Rather, only the body of the message is concealed and can only be decrypted with the private key of the intended recipient.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] This means that a third party could construct quite a detailed model of participants in a communication network, along with the subjects being discussed, even if the message body itself is hidden.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] However, there has been a recent demonstration of messaging with encrypted headers, which obscures the identities of the sender and recipient, and significantly reduces the available metadata to a third party.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] The concept is based around an open repository containing separately encrypted metadata blocks and encrypted messages.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Only the intended recipient is able to decrypt the metadata block, and having done so they can identify and download their messages and decrypt them.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Such a messaging system is at present in an experimental phase and not yet deployed.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Scaling this method would reveal to the third party only the inbox server being used by the recipient and the timestamp of sending and receiving.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] The server could be shared by thousands of users, making social network modelling much more challenging.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] During the early history of cryptography, two parties would rely upon a key that they would exchange by means of a secure, but non-cryptographic, method such as a face-to-face meeting, or a trusted courier.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] This key, which both parties must then keep absolutely secret, could then be used to exchange encrypted messages.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] A number of significant practical difficulties arise with this approach to distributing keys.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Here he described the relationship of one-way functions to cryptography, and went on to discuss specifically the factorization problem used to create a trapdoor function.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Ellis, a British cryptographer at the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), conceived of the possibility of "non-secret encryption", (now called public key cryptography), but could see no way to implement it.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] In 1973, his colleague Clifford Cocks implemented what has become known as the RSA encryption algorithm, giving a practical method of "non-secret encryption", and in 1974 another GCHQ mathematician and cryptographer, Malcolm J.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Williamson, developed what is now known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] The scheme was also passed to the US's National Security Agency.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Both organisations had a military focus and only limited computing power was available in any case; the potential of public key cryptography remained unrealised by either organization.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] These discoveries were not publicly acknowledged until the research was declassified by the British government in 1997.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] In 1976, an asymmetric key cryptosystem was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman who, influenced by Ralph Merkle's work on public key distribution, disclosed a method of public key agreement.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] This method of key exchange, which uses exponentiation in a finite field, came to be known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] This was the first published practical method for establishing a shared secret-key over an authenticated (but not confidential) communications channel without using a prior shared secret.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Merkle's "public key-agreement technique" became known as Merkle's Puzzles, and was invented in 1974 and only published in 1978.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] This makes asymmetric encryption a rather new field in cryptography although cryptography itself dates back more than 2,000 years.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] In 1977, a generalization of Cocks's scheme was independently invented by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, all then at MIT.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] The latter authors published their work in 1978 in Martin Gardner's Scientific American column, and the algorithm came to be known as RSA, from their initials.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] RSA uses exponentiation modulo a product of two very large primes, to encrypt and decrypt, performing both public key encryption and public key digital signatures.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Its security is connected to the extreme difficulty of factoring large integers, a problem for which there is no known efficient general technique.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] A description of the algorithm was published in the Mathematical Games column in the August 1977 issue of Scientific American.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] Since the 1970s, a large number and variety of encryption, digital signature, key agreement, and other techniques have been developed, including the Rabin signature, ElGamal encryption, DSA and ECC.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] In addition to the algorithms developed within the open academic and standards communities, several countries have developed national public-key cryptography standards for use within their jurisdictions.
[src:monero-privacy/public-key-cryptography] These include SM2 and SM9 (China), GOST R 34.10-2012 (Russia), EC-KCDSA (South Korea), and DSTU 4145 (Ukraine).
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] In cryptography, a **ring signature** is a type of digital signature that can be performed by any member of a set of users that each have keys.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] Therefore, a message signed with a ring signature is endorsed by someone in a particular set of people.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] One of the security properties of a ring signature is that it should be computationally infeasible to determine *which* of the set's members' keys was used to produce the signature.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] Ring signatures are similar to group signatures but differ in two key ways: first, there is no way to revoke the anonymity of an individual signature; and second, any set of users can be used as a signing set without additional setup.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] Ring signatures were invented by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir, and Yael Tauman Kalai, and introduced at ASIACRYPT in 2001.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] The name, *ring signature*, comes from the ring-like structure of the signature algorithm.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] Party *i* can compute a ring signature σ on a message *m*, on input (*m*, *S**i*, *P*1, ..., *P**n*).
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] Anyone can check the validity of a ring signature given σ, *m*, and the public keys involved, *P*1, ..., *P**n*.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] If a ring signature is properly computed, it should pass the check.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] On the other hand, it should be hard for anyone to create a valid ring signature on any message for any set without knowing any of the private keys for that set.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] In the original paper, Rivest, Shamir, and Tauman described ring signatures as a way to leak a secret.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] For instance, a ring signature could be used to provide an anonymous signature from "a high-ranking White House official", without revealing which official signed the message.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] Ring signatures are right for this application because the anonymity of a ring signature cannot be revoked, and because the group for a ring signature can be improvised.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] Another application, also described in the original paper, is for deniable signatures.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] Here the sender and the recipient of a message form a group for the ring signature, then the signature is valid to the recipient, but anyone else will be unsure whether the recipient or the sender was the actual signer.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] Thus, such a signature is convincing, but cannot be transferred beyond its intended recipient.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] The property of linkability allows one to determine whether any two signatures have been produced by the same member (under the same private key).
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] The identity of the signer is nevertheless preserved.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] In addition to the previous scheme the public key of the signer is revealed (if they issue more than one signatures under the same private key).
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] Most of the proposed algorithms have asymptotic output size $O(n)$ ; i.e., the size of the resulting signature increases linearly with the size of input (number of public keys).
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] That means that such schemes are impracticable for real use cases with sufficiently large n (for example, an e-voting with millions of participants).
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] But for some application with relatively small median input size such estimate may be acceptable.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] CryptoNote implements $O(n)$ ring signature scheme by Fujisaki and Suzuki in p2p payments to achieve sender's untraceability.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] More efficient algorithms have appeared recently.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] There are schemes with the sublinear size of the signature, as well as with constant size.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] The original paper describes an RSA based ring signature scheme, as well as one based on Rabin.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] The function $C_{k,v}(y_{1},y_{2},\dots ,y_{n})$ is called the ring equation, and is defined below.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] It outputs a single value z which is forced to be equal to v .
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] The equation $v=C_{k,v}(y_{1},y_{2},\dots ,y_{n})$ can be solved as long as at least one $y_{i}$ , and by extension $x_{i}$ , can be freely chosen.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] Under the assumptions of RSA, this implies knowledge of at least one of the inverses of the trap door functions $g_{i}^{-1}$ (i.e. a private key), since $g_{i}^{-1}(y_{i})=x_{i}$ .
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] Generating a ring signature involves six steps.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] The plaintext is signified by m , the ring's public keys by $P_{1},P_{2},\dots ,P_{n}$ .
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] Pick random $x_{i}$ for all ring members but yourself ( $x_{s}$ will be calculated using the **s**igner's private key), and calculate corresponding $y_{i}=g_{i}(x_{i})$ .
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] Signature verification involves three steps.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] Calculate the symmetric key $k={\mathcal {H}}(m)$ .
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] Here is a Python implementation of the original paper using RSA.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] Requires third-party module PyCryptodome.
[src:monero-privacy/ring-signature] Monero and several other cryptocurrencies use this technology.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] Launched in October 2016, Zcash was developed by cryptographers at Johns Hopkins University and MIT and derived its code from bitcoin.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] Zcash was one of the first large-scale implementations of zero-knowledge proofs outside of academia.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] Zcash is modeled on bitcoin, sharing its proof-of-work consensus mechanism.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] In 2016, Tom Robinson, co-founder of blockchain tracing firm Elliptic, told CNBC that Zcash appeared to have achieved a high level of anonymity.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] Zcash supports two types of addresses: transparent addresses, which function similarly to bitcoin addresses with publicly visible transactions, and shielded addresses, which use zero-knowledge proofs to encrypt transaction data.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] Shielded transactions can be verified as valid without revealing the sender, recipient, or amount transferred.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] Users can transact between the two types, allowing funds to move between the transparent and shielded pools.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] This optional privacy model is intended to preserve fungibility, allowing units of the currency to be treated equally regardless of their transaction history.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] Users also have the option to share private viewing keys, allowing designated third parties to see their transaction details for auditing purposes.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] A 2018 study found that while it is possible to use Zcash privately, the anonymity set of the shielded pool could be reduced through heuristics-based analysis of usage patterns.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] The analysis predates subsequent protocol upgrades to the shielded transaction system.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] In 2022, journalist Andy Greenberg described Zcash's shielded transactions as "provably inaccessible" to surveillance and said he had not seen evidence that its anonymity could be compromised.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] Development work on Zcash began in 2013 by Johns Hopkins University professor Matthew Green and his graduate students Ian Miers and Christina Garman, who developed the Zerocoin protocol.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] They subsequently joined forces with a team of cryptographers including Alessandro Chiesa and Madars Virza from MIT, and Eli Ben-Sasson from the Technion and Eran Tromer from Tel Aviv University, who had developed a more efficient variant called zk-SNARKs.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] The development was completed by the for-profit Zcash Company, led by Zooko Wilcox, a Colorado based computer security specialist.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] The Zcash Company raised over $3 million from investors including Naval Ravikant.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] Zcash was first mined in late October 2016.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] To generate revenue, 10% of all coins mined for the first four years were automatically distributed to the Zcash Company and the Zcash Foundation.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] The instantiation of the Zcash network required the creation of a master private key.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] To ensure privacy, this private key must later be destroyed, otherwise counterfeit Zcash coins could be generated.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] To maximize the chance that no one person could obtain the private key, software was written which allowed individuals from six different locations to collaboratively generate the private key, use it to instantiate Zcash, and then destroy the computers used in the process afterwards.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] In 2019, Electric Coin Company researcher Sean Bowe discovered Halo, a technique for generating zero-knowledge proofs without requiring a trusted setup ceremony.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] This eliminated the need for the elaborate multi-party ceremonies used at launch.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] In 2018, *MIT Technology Review* named Zcash co-founder Alessandro Chiesa, an assistant professor at the University of California, Berkeley, to its Innovators Under 35 list for his work on the zero-knowledge proof technology underlying the cryptocurrency.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] In 2022, Edward Snowden revealed that he had participated in the creation of Zcash under the pseudonym "John Dobbertin." Other participants in the ceremony included Peter Todd, a Bitcoin Core developer.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] On February 21, 2019, the "Zcash Company" announced a rebranding as the Electric Coin Company (ECC).
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] In 2020, the Electric Coin Company transitioned to nonprofit ownership, becoming a wholly owned subsidiary of the Bootstrap Project, a 501(c)(3) organization.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] In September 2023, a mining pool named ViaBTC had seized control of over half the hashing power on Zcash.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] This 51% dominance raised worries about a 51% attack, where they could potentially manipulate transactions and harm the network.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] In response, Coinbase placed Zcash markets into "limit-only" mode in an effort to prevent significant price swings.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] In November 2025, Cameron Winklevoss and Tyler Winklevoss invested $50 million to launch Cypherpunk Technologies, a digital-asset treasury company focused on the cryptocurrency.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] Securities and Exchange Commission closed a probe into Zcash.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] In April 2026, Foundry, one of the largest bitcoin mining pool operators, launched a dedicated Zcash mining pool.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] In 2017, JPMorgan Chase integrated Zcash's zero-knowledge proof technology into its enterprise blockchain platform Quorum to enable confidential transactions for business clients.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] *Fortune* reported that Zcash's fundamental technology would be added to the Ethereum network.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] In late 2017, Grayscale Investments launched a Zcash investment fund, which is the company's third dedicated cryptocurrency fund after bitcoin and Ethereum Classic.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] In 2026, Grayscale filed with regulators to convert the fund into an exchange-traded fund.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] In May 2018, the New York State Department of Financial Services approved Zcash for trading on Gemini.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] The Freedom of the Press Foundation, the Human Rights Foundation, and the Electronic Frontier Foundation have accepted Zcash donations.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] In 2017, the European Union's law enforcement agency Europol flagged Zcash, along with bitcoin and Monero, for potential use in internet-based crime.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] The same report noted that Zcash was not known to have a significant criminal following.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] In 2018, several Japanese exchanges delisted Zcash and other privacy-focused cryptocurrencies citing regulatory pressure following a major exchange hack; the delisted coins had not been involved in the hack.
[src:monero-privacy/zcash] A 2023 analysis of cryptocurrency and crime similarly found that Zcash "featured very rarely on the dark web" compared to Monero.
